column37: Manuscript Bible with most of the prologues typical of a Paris Bible but with the Interpretationes Hebraicorum nominum following Psaland with punctuation suggesting English origin. Lacking the first leaf of the New Testament (containing Jerome's prologue to the New Testament and Matthew before f. 285). Annotated with references to works of Albertus Magnus the glossa ordinaria and the Sentences of Peter Lombard in a number of hands from the 13th through 15th centuries likely by Dominican owners or readers.

column37: The manuscript was produced in Italy but was decorated by a French and an Italian illuminator. The French artist was largely responsible for illumination from Jerome's Prologue up to Isaiah (fol. 264) where the Italian illuminator takes over although some decoration after this point indicates either a third artist or the French and Italian illuminator working together.
